.TH _PRINTF 3 "November 2025" "Holberton School" "Library Functions Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- custom implementation of the standard printf function

.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
#include "main.h"

int _printf(const char *format, ...);
.fi

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf()
function produces output according to a format string.
It writes the output to the standard output stream (stdout).

The function handles zero or more format specifiers.
Each specifier is introduced by the '%' character.

This simplified version supports the following conversion specifiers:

.TP
.B %c
Prints a single character.

.TP
.B %s
Prints a string. If the string is NULL, "(null)" is printed.

.TP
.B %%
Prints a literal '%' character.

.TP
.B %d
Prints a signed decimal integer.

.TP
.B %i
Prints a signed decimal integer (same as %d).

.PP
This implementation does not handle:
flags, field width, precision, length modifiers, buffers,
or any specifiers other than those listed above.

.SH RETURN VALUE
The
.B _printf()
function returns the number of characters printed
(excluding the terminating null byte used to end C strings).

On error, a negative value is returned.

.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
_printf("Hello %s\\n", "world");
     → Prints: Hello world

_printf("Number: %d\\n", 123);
     → Prints: Number: 123

_printf("Percent: %%\\n");
     → Prints: Percent: %
.fi

.SH AUTHORS
Dényss Paricard, Bernis kourou

.SH SEE ALSO
printf(3)

.SH NOTES
This is a simplified academic project and
should not be used as a replacement for the standard printf.
